# GDScript Code Documentation

Follow Godot's official documentation format for all `.gd` files. Use `##` documentation comments that appear in the editor help window.

## Documentation Comment Format

- Use `##` (double hash) for documentation comments.
- Place documentation immediately before the member or script it describes.
- Use `[br]` for line breaks to keep documentation readable when descriptions span multiple sentences.

## Script-Level Documentation (Top of File)

Place at the top of the script, after `extends` and before any members:

```gdscript
## Brief description of the class's role and functionality (under ~200 characters).
##
## Extended description of what the script does,[br]
## how it works, and any further detail.
##
## @tutorial: https://example.com  # Optional
## @deprecated: Use [OtherClass] instead.  # If applicable
## @experimental  # If API is unstable
```

## Member Documentation Order (Match Code Order)

Document members in the same order they appear in code:

1. **signals** → 2. **enums** (document each enum value) → 3. **constants** → 4. **@export variables** → 5. **regular variables** → 6. **@onready variables** → 7. **methods** (`_init`, `_ready`, virtual callbacks, then custom methods)

## BBCode Tags (Use Consistently)

| Tag | Use |
|-----|-----|
| `[br]` | Line break for readability |
| `[code]value[/code]` | Inline code, literals, arguments |
| `[param name]` | Parameter names in method docs |
| `[member Class.name]` | Link to property |
| `[method Class.name]` | Link to method |
| `[signal Class.name]` | Link to signal |
| `[constant Class.name]` | Link to constant |
| `[enum Class.name]` | Link to enum |
| `[b]text[/b]` | Bold emphasis |

## Writing Guidelines (Strict)

- **Active voice**: "Returns the value" not "The value is returned".
- **Precise verbs**: Use `position`, `rotate`, `fade` instead of generic `set`, `make`.
- **Avoid -ing verbs** for instant actions: "stops" not "stopping".
- **Ban these 8 words**: obvious, simple, basic, easy, actual, just, clear, however.
- **Explicit references**: Repeat names instead of "the former" or "the latter".
- **Possession**: Use `'s` (e.g., "the node's position").
- **Oxford comma**: "A, B, and C".
- **Booleans**: Describe as "If [code]true[/code], ..." or "If [code]false[/code], ...".
- **Return values**: End method docs with "Returns ..." when relevant (skip for `set_`/`get_` methods).

## Examples

```gdscript
## Emitted when the door opens.
signal door_opened

## Direction to move. Use with [method move_toward].
enum Direction {
	## Move up.
	UP,
	## Move down.
	DOWN,
}

## Maximum movement speed in pixels per second.
const MAX_SPEED := 200.0

## If [code]true[/code], the node processes input each frame.
@export var process_input: bool = true

## Transitions to the target screen.[br]
## Pass [param metadata] to call [method set_edit_data] on the new screen.
func change_screen(screen: Screen, metadata: Variant = null) -> void:
	pass
```

## Complete Script Example

```gdscript
class_name MyNode
extends Node
## Brief overview of the node's role.
##
## Extended description of functionality.[br]
## Use [br] to separate logical sections.

## Emitted when processing completes.
signal processing_completed

## Processing mode.
enum Mode {
	## Idle mode.
	IDLE,
	## Active mode.
	ACTIVE,
}

## Default timeout in seconds.
const DEFAULT_TIMEOUT := 5.0

## If [code]true[/code], starts automatically.
@export var autostart := false

var _timer: float = 0.0

@onready var _label: Label = %Label


func _ready() -> void:
	_connect_signals()


## Starts the processing cycle.[br]
## Returns [code]true[/code] if started successfully.
func start() -> bool:
	return true
```
